# Commit messages

When asked to propose or write a commit message (or after summarizing repo changes for a commit), follow this.

## Inspect changes

1. Run `git status` and `git diff --cached` (or `git diff` if nothing is staged) to see what would be committed.
2. Summarize the changes accurately; do not invent scope or files that are not in the diff.

## Format (Conventional Commits)

Output **one** plaintext fenced code block containing the **full** message only—suitable to paste into vim or pipe to `git commit -F -`. Do not wrap the subject or body in extra commentary outside that block.

### Line width (inside the code block)

- **Subject line (first line):** one line only; prefer about **50 characters** or fewer; do not exceed **72 characters** on that line.
- **Blank line** after the subject before the body.
- **Body and bullets:** hard-wrap at **72 characters per line** (count spaces). Break at word boundaries; indent wrapped continuation lines for list items so wrapped text stays readable (aligned under the text after the bullet marker).

Leave URLs, file paths, or opaque identifiers on their own line when breaking them would be worse than a long line.

```
type(scope): brief description

- Change 1
- Change 2 that runs long and continues on the next line with
  matching indentation when needed
```

Use a real `type` (e.g. `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`) and an optional `scope` when it clarifies the area. Keep the subject line imperative and concise; use the bullet list for substantive points.

## Repo policy

Follow `.cursor/rules/git-workflow.mdc` for when to commit.

- **Handoff / implementation work:** When implementing from `docs/handoffs/`
  or when the user asks you to build a feature and keep git updated, use
  `git add` (narrowly) and `git commit` with a message in the format above.
  Commit after each logical milestone.
- **Otherwise:** Do not run `git commit`, `git add`, or `git stash` unless the
  user explicitly asked for git writes. Inspecting with `git status` /
  `git diff` for message drafting is always fine.
